         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ bot Garden ¶ 28/2/73 ¶  ¶ It affords me very much pleasure, dear Mr Wallace, to send you such seeds of comparatively hardy plants as I have just at hand. I would advise you to have a porti...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.02.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alfred Russel Wallace</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">British Library, London, Alfred Russel Wallace papers, additional manuscripts 46435, ff 262-3.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/2/73</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It affords me very much pleasure, dear Mr Wallace, to send you such seeds of comparatively hardy plants as I have just at hand. I would advise you to have a portion of each sown in the Channel islands and elsewhere, so that the chances of your not only raising, but also establishing such plants may be augmented. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If you can in your rambles secure for me any well ripened seeds of English forest flowers and water-plants for naturalisation of such plants in Australia, I should feel very much indebted.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you allow me to send my poor photogram and ask for yours to be placed in my album of pictures of celebrated scientific travellers.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The seeds go to the care of Dr Hooker.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Wallace, in beginning his correspondence with M, had asked Hooker for permission to use his name and to send his card to M. Hooker replied, 'By all means use my name &amp; send my card to Mueller. Entre nous, do not forget the Baron von - he is as vain as a peacock' (J. Hooker to A. R. Wallace, 26 November 1872; British Library, BL Add. 46435, ff. 258-9 (Beccaloni (ed.) <ref target="https://epsilon.ac.uk/view/wallace/letters/WCP2292"
                          rend="Internet%20link"
                          style="color: #0000ff; ">
                        <seg rend="Internet%20link" style="color: #0000ff; ">https://epsilon.ac.uk/view/wallace/letters/WCP2292</seg>
                     </ref> [accessed 24 April 2022]).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The remainder of the text is written on one side of f. 263.</p>
               </note>I may be able to send you <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">soon</hi>
               </seg> some seeds of Australian alpine plants<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Wallace had apparently asked for seeds of hardy alpine plants (J. Hooker to A. R. Wallace, see n. 1 above: 'I shall be glad to hear if you succeed with any of the Australian alpines. We have failed with them uniformly'). Wallace acknowledged the receipt of the seeds in a letter to J. Hooker, 30 April 1873 ((Beccaloni (ed.) <ref target="https://epsilon.ac.uk/view/wallace/letters/WCP4742"
                          rend="Internet%20link"
                          style="color: #0000ff; ">
                        <seg rend="Internet%20link" style="color: #0000ff; ">
                           <seg style="color: #1915f5; ">https://epsilon.ac.uk/view/wallace/letters/WCP4742</seg>
                        </seg>
                     </ref>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="2"/>[accessed 24 April 2022]).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Would you oblige me, by giving me the adresses of any friends of yours in tropical America, willing to send me in exchange of seeds of showy Australian plants (such as the <name key="Callistemon">Callistemon</name>s &amp;c) seeds of <name key="Bambusaceae">Bambusaceae</name>, Palms &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Have any special publications on New Guinea recently appeared? If so, pray put Mess Dulau &amp; co in the way to send them to me.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bambusaceae">Bambusaceae</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Callistemon">Callistemon</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
